{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_havarti_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542868983/1927021201/0086.xml":{"full_text":"BANK TRANSACTIONS\nFriday, Feb. 11, 1927\n$20,938,364\nAll banks reported.\nBelieve Coolidge Will Veto McNary-Haugen Bill\nSENATE PASSES\nFARM MEASURE\nBY EIGHT VOTES\nSimilar Action Ex\npected in Lower\nHouse Monday.\nBY PAUL R. MALLON.\nStaff Correspondent\nThe I\u2019nited Press\nWASHINGTON The McNary-\nHaugen farm relief bill has com\npleted the first leg of its journey\nto the white house.\nWith less than a week of debate,\nthe farm bloc forced the bill\nthrough the senate late yesterday\nand sent it today upon its way to\nthe house, where similar favorable\naction is expected Monday or Tues\nday.\n\u201cI do not know what President\nCoolidge will do with the bill if it\ncomes to him for signature, but he\ncannot help being impressed by the\ndecisive vote,\u201d chairman McNary\nof the senate agriculture committe,\nco-author of the measure, told the\nUnited Press after the bill had been\nadopted, 47 to 39.\nUP to Coolidge.\nThe bill should be finally perfect\ned by both houses the latter part of\nnext week. Then it will go to the\npresident, who can pocket it until\ncongress adjourns, veto it or sign it\nand make it a law.\nApparetnly authentic information\nhas unofficially been given Repub\nlican leaders that Coolidge will veto\nthe bill.\nThe farm bloc in the house, is\nmaking preparations to rush action\non th* bill. A similar bill already\nis under consideration, and the sen\nate bill will be substituted for it.\nAbout the 12 hours allotted for\ndebate have been utilized..\nHave 40-Vote Margin.\nHouse farm leaders assert they\nhave a 40-vote margin for the meas\nure.\nThe senate farm bloc smashed the\nbill through so speedily yesterday\nthat it did not take time to correct\nsome of the amendments. A techni\ncal amendment by Senator McKel\nlar, Democrat, Tennessee, was side\ntracked, but will be inserted in the\nhouse.\nSeveral far-reaching amendments\nwere adpoted by the senate. Tobac\nco was inserted in the list of com\nmodities affected by the equaliza\ntion fee. along with wheat, corn,\nswine, rice and cotton.\n24 Republicans Vote \u201cYes.\u201d\nA provision was entered to enable\na majority of co-operative organiza\ntions of any state to reject the\nequalization fee feature of the bill\nfor that state.\nArizona, Oregon, Washington,\nNorth and South Dakota,\nKansas, Minnesota, Indiana. Illi\nnois, Oklahoma, Arkansas, Texas,\nLouisiana, Florida and Tennessee\nwere solidly for the bill. Twenty\nfour Republicans voted for the\nmeasure.\nNorthern Pacific\nValuation Fixed\nWASHINGTON Tentative val\nuation for the Northern Pacific rail\nway was fixed by the interstate\ncommerce commission today as of\nJune 30, 1917, at $417,217,935 total\nowned and $415,255,915 total used\nproperty. The company\u2019s capitali\nzation is estimated at $609,123,954.\nThe Northern Pacific operates\n6,900 miles of track.\nMilwaukee Livestock\nHOGS \u2014Receipts, 700; 25c lower.\nPrime heavy and butchers,\n200 to 350 pounds $11.20@11.60\nPrime heavy and butchers,\n200 to 250 pounds 11.50@11.i0\nPair to good light, 160 to 200 11.50@12.00\nFrosh light lights. 130 to 160 11.50@12.10\nFair to select packers 10,50 @ll.OO\nFair to rough packers..... 10.00@10.40\nPigs and light lights 10.00@11.50\nGovernment throwouts 1.00 8.00\nBoars I.oo\u00ae 7.00\nCATTLE \u2014Receipts, 200; steady.\nSteers, good to choice I 9.00@11.00\nMedium to good B.oo@ 9.00\nFair to medium 7.25 8.50\nSteers, common 5.00@ 7.00\nHeifers, good to choice..... 7.00@ 8.00\nHeifers, medium to g00d... 6.00@ 6.75\nFair to medium 5.50@ 6.00\nCommon to fair 4.50 5.00\nCows, good to choice 5.50 6.00\nMedium to good 4.75\u00a9 5.25\nFair to medium 5.00@ 5.25\nCutters 4.50@ 4.75\nCanners 4.00@ 4.25\nButchers\u2019 bulls 7.00@ 7.25\nBologna bulls 5,50@ 6,25\nMilkers and springers, good\nto choice (common sell\nfor beef) 60.00@55.00\nCALVES \u2014Receipts, 500; steady.\nGood to choice, 100 lbs. up.512,75@13.25\nFair to good 12.00@12.50\nThrowouts 6.00 7.00\nSHEEP \u2014Receipts, 100; steady.\nGood to choice ewes and\nwether lambs $12.25@12.75\nMedium to good 11.00@12.00\nHeavy bulk lambs 9.00@10.00\nLight ewes 5.00 8.00\nCull ewes E.so@ 6.50\nBucks 4.50@ 5.00\nCHICAGO GRAIN RANGE.\nJames E. Bennett Co.\nPrevious\nWheat\u2014High. Low. Close. Close.\nMay 1.41% 1.40% 1.41 1.41%\nJuly 1.35 1.34% 1.34% 1.34%\nSept 1.32% 1.32% 1.32% 1.32%\nCorn\nMay 81% 80% 81% SO%\nJuly 84% 84% 84% 84%\nSept 87 56% 86% 86%\nOats\u2014\u25a0\nMay 46% 46% 46% 46%\nJuly 47 46% 47 47\nSept 45% 45% 45% 45%\nLard-\nMay 12.55 12.42 12.42 12.55\nRibs\u2014\nMay 14.70 14.85\nRyp-\nMay 1.07% 1.06% 1.06% 1.07%\nJuly 1.04% 1.03% 1.04% 1.04%\nSept 99% 99% 99% 99%\nPRIMARY GRAIN MOVEMENT.\nPrimary car receipts today follow:\nWht. Corn Oats Barley Rye\nMilwaukee, 5 42 9 13 5\nChicago 8 61 40 6 2\nMinneapolis 148 14 11 22 7\nDuluth 65 3 42\nWinnipeg 895 SO 64 6\nKansas City 174 41 2\nSt. Louis ..64 SO 22\nOmaha, 29 32 IS M 3\nThe Leader Financial Page\nEla Threatens to\nDiscontinue State\nTobacco \u2018Pool\u2019\nVIROQUA \u2014Unless farmers with\nin the next two months manifested\ngreater support of their pool, he\nwill recommend to the board of di\nrectors at their April meeting that\nit discontinue the pool, Emerson\nEla, business director of the Wis\nconsin Tobacco pool, told 300 grow\ners here today.\n\u201cThe house of the pool is in\nshape,\u201d he said in issuing his chal\nlenge, \u201cwe have only a small\namount of tobacco on hand, all of\nwhich could be sold on 24 hours\nnotice.\n\u201cHowever, unless enough con\ntracts are signed between now and\nApril to warrant continuance, I will\nrecommend to the directors that\nthey wind up the pool.\u201d\nJANUARY TRADE\nPLEASES BRITAIN\nLONDON\u2014-January trade returns\nhave revived the British hopes for\na business revival following last\nyear\u2019s disaster occasioned by the\ncoal strike.\nJanuary exports showed a $28,-\n500,000 jump over December in the\nboard of trade figures, and the to\ntal exports for the month exceeded\n$275,000,000. Imports increased\nonly $1,040,000, leaving a substan\ntial balance on the favorable side.\nThe January exports of coal\namounted to 4,092,000 tons,, only\n$50,000 tons below January of last\nyear. But as a matter of fact the\nvalue of this year\u2019s exports whs\n$2,500,000 more than last January,\nbecause of the better prices ob\ntained.\nThe total exports last month\namounted to $325,000,000 and im\nports amounted to $565,000,000.\nIron and steel production and\nmanufactured articles increased\n$5,000,000. Earthenware increased\n$1,000,000. Cotton yarn manufac\ntures jumped $32,500,000. Woolen\nand worsted yarns and manufac\ntures increased nearly $5,000,000.\nSante Fe Official\nLeaps to Death\nFrom Hospital\nSAN FRANCISCO Edward\nChambers, Chicago, vice-president\nOf the Atchison, Topeka Santa Fe\nrailroad, was instantly killed here\nyesterday after he had leaped from\nthe fourth story of a hospital where\nhe had been undergoing treatment\nfor a minor operation.\nMr. Chambers was nationally\nknown as a railroad executive. He\nhad been with the Santa Fe for 49\nyears. He was 68 years old.\nDuring the war Mr. Chambers\nwas made director of transportation\nof the United States* food adminis\ntration and later was director of\ntraffic of the United States railroad\nadministration under Diretcor Gen\neral William G. McAdoo and later\nWalter D. Hines.\nThree sons, Edward, San Fran\ncisco: Robert, Los Angeles, and\nWalter Chambers, formerly of Chi\ncago, and one daughter, a nun in\nthe Holy Family convent at San\nFrancisco, survive.\nWisconsin Public\nService Company\u2019s\nEarnings Jump\nGross earnings of the Wisconsin\nPublic Service corporation during\nthe year came to $4,454,565, com\npared with $3,980,288 in 1925, an\nincrease of nearly $475,000, it was\nannounced yesterday.\nNet, after taxes and other deduc\ntions, came to $1,846,220, against\n$1,527,789 the year following.\nThe figure given for interest was\n$899,019, compared with $684,397,\nand for preferred dividends $283,\n344, ^gainst $210,877.\nMilwaukee Produce Prices\u2014Corrected Daily\nDAIRY MARKETS.\nButter\u2014Creamery, fresh, extras, tubs,\n50c; extra firsts, 48@49c; centralized,\n8S to 89 score, 49c; ladles, 38@40c;\npacking stock No. 1, 30@33c; off-stock,\n15@20c.\nCheese American, full cream, twins,\n25@25%c; daisies, single, 25%@26c;\ndouble, 25%@26c; Young Americas, 26@\n26%c; longhorns, 26@26%c; squares,\n25% 26c. 5-lb. loaves \u2014American, 31\n33c; pimento, 34@J6c; brick, 32@34c;\nSwiss, 38 41c. Special makes \u2014Brick,\nfancy, 23%@21c; limburger, 25@26c;\nSwiss, block, 26 29c; loaf, 30@36e; im\nported, Swiss, 42 45c.\nEggs\u2014Fresh-gathered firsts, standard\ncases Included, 33@34c; ordinary firsts,\nshippers' cases Included, 30 31c; dirties,\ncandled. 26 27c; seconds, checks, can\ndied, 25@26c.\nMEATS AND POULTRY.\nPigeons Old flyers, live, per doz.,\n$1.25; dead, 95c; squabs, live, per doz.,\n$1.50@2.00; dressed, fat. $2.00@2.50;\nthin, poorly dressed, $1.00@1.50.\nRabbits\u2014Per doz., $1.75 @2.00; Jacks,\n$2.00@2.50.\nPoultry\u2014Live\u2014Fowls, heavy, 4% lbs.,\n26c; light, 22c; roosters, l-9@2oc; spring\ners, fancy, heavy, 26c; mediumweights,\n23@24c; leghorns, 22c; turkeys, plump,\n30c; ducks, 28@30c: geese, 20@22c;\nGuinea hens, per dozen, old, $5.00;\nyoung, $6.00.\nDressed Poultry\u2014Turkeys, young toms.\n45c; old toms, 38c; prime young hens,\n40c; old hens, 36c; No. 2s,- 28@30c;\nducks, fancy, 34c; ordinary, 25c; spring\ners, fancy, 27@28c; fowls, heavy, 28@\n29c; old roosters, 20@22c.\nVeai\u2014Calves, 50 to 60 lbs., fair kid\nneys, 12@13c; 60 to 70 lbs., choice,\nmeaty, 13@14c; 70 to 80 lbs., good kid\nneys, 14@15c; 80 to 90 lbs., choice 15@\n16c; 90 to 110 lbs., fancy, bright, 16@\n17c; thin, bony, poor kidneys, poorly\ndressed or off-stock. 80 to 175 lbs., as\nto quality and condition. 9@llc.\nHides\u2014Calf, green, 17c; cured, 18c;\nkips, green, 12c; cured, 13c; cow, green,\n7c; cured. 8c; bull, green, sc; cured, 6c;\ndeacons, green, each. 60c; slunk, green,\neach 25c; horse No. 1, green, each, $3.50;\ndo. No. 2 green, each, $2.25; pelts, green,\neach, 50c@51.50.\nFRUITS.\nApples Michigan or Wisconsin, per\nbushel, 75c@1.25; barrels, $3.00@4.00;\nWestern, boxes, Jonathans, $2.25@2.50:\nDelicious, $3,50@4.00; Spitzenberg, $2.50\nTEN\n$10,000,000\nPOWER DEAL\nMilwaukee men are among the or\nganizers of a $10,000,000 holding\ncompany formed in Omaha which\nwill operate public utility properties\nowned and controlled by it in 129\ncities of lowa, Nebraska, Minnesota\nand the Dakotas.\nThe Milwaukee men are Walter\nN. Albertson, George W. Kalweit,\nR. C. Hill and E. T. Sadler. They\nare to be president, vice-president,\noperating engineer and auditor, re\nspectively, of the new holding cor\nporation, it is reported.\nMr. Albertson, president of the\nW. N. Albterson Co., First Wiscon\nsin Bank building, is now in Omaha,\nand expects to move to that city\nsoon to establish the business head\nquarters of the new enterprise.\nIt is reported that the McGraw\nElectric Co. of Omaha will own\npractically all the common stock\nand will have control of the parent\ncompany and the Central West Pub\nlic Service Co., Inc.\nGoodyear Tire Co.\nPuts Net Profits\nAt $8,799,138\nNEW YORK\u2014The Goodyear Tire\nRubber Co. carried net profits of\n$8,799,138 to surplus in 1926, ac\ncording to its annual report issued\ntoday.\nThis was after providing $7,494,-\n122 for depreciation of plants and\nequipment; after charging excess\ncost of rubber and cotton in net\namount of $5,250,000 to the special\nraw material reserve set up in\n1925; after all taxes, interest and\nother charges, and after deducting\nprofits of subsidiary companies ap\nplicable to stock not held by the\nGoodyear company.\nThe net sales of the consolidated\ngroup of companies for the year\nwere $230,161,356, compared with\n$205,999,829 in 1925, an increase of\nabout 12 per cent. Total assets are\nlisted in the report at $178,965,325.\nFailures in Week\nIncrease to <594\nNEW YORK\u2014In contrast to last\nweek\u2019s improvement, the record of\nfailures in the United States this\nweek shows an increase, the num\nber being 594.\nThis is 24 more than the total re\nported to R. G. Dun Co. last week,\nthe increase being principally in the\nsouth. Except for the west all sec\ntions of the country had more de\nfaults this week. In the west, the\ndecrease is 11 insolvencies.\nA year ago,, when the returns cov\nered five business days only, the\nnu iber of failures was 381. Few r er\ndefaults occurred in Canada this\nweek, the number being 50. This is\nnine less than last week\u2019s total.\nWholesale Prices\nWASHINGTON\u2014Check payments\nduring the first week of February,\nindicative of the general volume of\ntrade, were larger than in either\ncomparative period.\nThe production of bituminous coal\nin the last week of January was\nlarger then in either the preceding\nweek or the corresponding week of\n1926. Lumber production during the\nlast week of January was smaller\nthan in either the preceding week or\nthe same week of the previous year.\nThe volume of goods moving into\nconsumption, as seen from data on\ncarloadings, was greater in the last\nweek of January than in either the\nprevious week or the corresponding\nweek of 1926.\nANTIGO \u2014The next state grain\nshow of the Wisconsin Experiment\nAssn, will be held here in Novem\nber, according to word received by\nthe Langlade county agricultural\nagent.\n2.75; Wine Saps, $2.E0@3.00; barrels,\nNew York Greenings, $4.50 @5.25.\nBananas\u2014Per 100 lbs.. $6.00 @7.00.\nGrapes\u2014California, Table Grapes,, Al\nmerlas, kegs. $7.50 @B.OO.\nGrape Fruit\u2014Florida, per box, as Vj\nsize and quality, $3.50@4.50.\nLemons \u2014California, per box, $5.00\n5.50.\nLimes\u2014lmported, 100, $2.00@2.25.\nOranges California, new Navels, per\nbox, ns to size and quality. $5.00@6.00:\nFlorida, $4.50@5.00; Indian Rivers, $5.50\n@6.00.\nTangerines\u2014Florida, boxes, $3.25@\n3.50.\nPears\u2014Western, boxes. Winter Welles,\n$3 75 @4.00.\nPineapples\u2014Cuban, crate, $5.00@5.50.\nBERRIES.\nCranberries\u2014Cape Cods, boxes, Wis\nconsin, $3.75@4.00; Eastern, $4.25@4.50. t\nStrawberries\u2014Florida, quarts, sl.lo@\n1.25; pints, 60@65c.\nVEGETABLES.\nBeets Home-grown, bushels. 90c\n$1.00; new, Texas, bushels, $1.5C@2.00.\nCabbage Home-grown, bushel, 40\n50c; barrels, $1.25@1.50; Holland seed, I\nper ton, $10.00@12.00; new, Texas, crate,\n$2,00@2.25; bulk, bbls., $1.75@2.00.\nCarrots Home-grown, bushels, 65@\n75c; new, Texas, bushel, $1.25@1.75.\nCauliflower\u2014California, crate, $2.00\n2.25.\nCelery\u2014Michigan, square crates. $1.50\n@1.75; home-grown, doz. bunches, 50@\n75c; California, crate, $4.00@5.00; Flor\nida. $2.50@2.75.\nCelery noot \u2014Home-grown, doz.. as to\nsize, 25@60c.\nCucumbers\u2014Hot house, boxes, 2 doz.,\nextra fancy, $6.00@6.50; home-grown,\ndoz., $2.00@2.50.\nEgg Plant \u2014-Florida, crate, $6.00@6.50.\nGarlic\u2014California, per lb\u201e 6@Bc.\nGreen Peas\u2014California, crates, $9.00\n10.00.\nHorseradish Southern, root, per lb.,\nlancy. thick. B@loc.\nLeek Home-grown, per bunch, 12\nstalks, large, 40c; small. 25@30c.\nLettuce Leaf Home-grown, hot\nhouse, doz. bunches, 40@45c.\nLettuce^\u2014Head \u2014Iceberg, fancy. West\nern, $3.00@3.25; off-stock. $1.50@2.00.\nMushrooms\u2014Per lb.. No. 1. 1-Ib boxes.\n65@70c: buttons, 50@60c.\nOnions \u2014Yelow, sacks, per 100 lbs.,\nWestern, 43.25@3.50; home-grown, 51.75\n@2.00; Spanish, per crate, $2.25@2.50;\nValencias, crate. 3.25@3.50,\nOyster Flant \u2014Fei doz. bunches, SI.OO\nAverage Lower\nPLAN GRAIN SHOW.\nMILWAUKEE, SATURDAY, FEBRUARY 12, 1927\nTexas Governor\nRepeals Guaranty\nAUSTIN, Tex. \u2014Gov. Dan Moody\ntoday signed the bill passed by the\nlegislature repealing the guaranty\nfund plan and the bond security\nsystem of protecting deposits in\nstate banks.\nThe bill carried the emergency\nclause and became immediately\neffective. The measure, however,\ngives bonded banks at least one\nyear in which to cancel the bonds\nexecuted to protect depositors.\nPassage of this measure means\nthat in the future all state banks,\nlike national banks, will have to\nstand on their own resources.\n8,000 Added to\nFrench \u2018Jobless\u2019\nPARIS \u2014An increase of more\nthan 8,000 in France\u2019s unemployed\nworkers was recorded in the last\nweek, according to official figures\npublished today by the ministry of\nworks.\nIt said that 64,434 were not list\ned, of -whom 47,627 are men and\n16,807 women. A w\u2019eek ago the num\nber of unemployed was registered at\n56,275, of whom 41,698 were men.\nThe metal industry heads the list\nof unoccupied, having 10,512 unem\nployed, 8,680 beng men.\nCoal and wood are next with\n4,831, the building trades 3,912, the\nclothing industry 3,883, chiefly\nwomen.\nMarshall Field\u2019s\nDry Gqods Review\nCHlCAGO\u2014Marshall Field Co.,\nIn their W\u2019eekly review of the whole\nsale dry goods trade, say:\n\u201cCurrent wholesale distribution\nof dry goods maintained about the\nsame volume as last week but did\nnot quite reach the figure recorded\nfor the same week last year.\n\u201cCollections were about the same\nas for the corresponding period a\nyear ago.\u201d\nt\nDurant Expects\nStocks to Mount\nNEW YURK\u2014William C. Durant,\na spectacularly successful stock\nmarket operator, believes that stocks\nof real merit will sell higher and\nthat many new high levels will be\nestablished. His views attracted\nattention in the financial district\nyesterday because of the announce\nment that he had postponed a trip\nto Europe giving rise to the belief\nthat he will continue to be an ag\ngressive factor in the market.\nMexican Crude Oil\nShows Decrease\nTAMPICO, Mex.\u2014 Production of\nlight heavy crude oil in Mexico in\n1926 totaled 89,028,506, barrels, a\ndecrease of 26,494,811 barrels from\n1925 withdrawals. This decrease\noccurred in spite of all efforts of the\ncompanies to bring in new produc\ntion, as more wells were-drilled in\n1926 than had been drilled in 1925.\nReal Estate Deals\nTop 1926 Mark\nReal estate activity in Milwaukee\nis more brisk here now than it was\nat this time last year, according to\nfigures issued yesterday by Phillip\nC. Westfahl, register of deeds.\nDuring January 1,590 warranty\ndeeds were recorded, compared with\n1,388 the same month a year ago.\nThere were 1.707 mortgages total\ning $8,260,301.32 filed during the\nmonth, against 1,570, amounting to\n$7,375,655.51. in January, 1926. and\n1,996, valued at $10,550,310.97, in\nDecember.\nExactly 100 land contracts repre\nsenting $1,378,335.34 were recorded,\ncompared with 87, amounting to\n$1,044,234.97, a year ago, and 137,\naggregating $1,590,855, a month ago.\nPLYMOUTH\u2014WeekIy cheese quota\ntions announced here are as follows:\nWisconsin Cheese exchange, 1,000 twins,\n22%c; 210 twins (not sold); Farmers\u2019\nCall board: 425 horns at 23%c; 50\nsquares at 23%c; 13 daisies at 23%c.\n@l.lO.\nParsley JElome-grown, dozen small\nbunches, 25@30c.\nParsnips Home-grown, bu\u201e washed,\nsl.oo@ 1.25; unwashed, 65@75c.\nPeppers\u2014Mexican, crates, $6.00 @6.50.\nPieplant\u2014Michigan, hot house, 5 lb.\nboxes, $1.00@1.25; home-grown, per lb.,\n10 15c.\nPotatoes \u2014Minnesota, Missouri, sacks,\n100 lbs., white stock, on track, $1.85@\n2.00; Idaho, rurals, $2.75@3.00; russets.\n?3.00@3.25.\nPotatoes \u2014New \u2014Florida, per bbl.. No.\n1. $16.00 @17.00; No. 2, $14.00@14.50.\nRadishes Home-grown, doz. bchs.,\nhot house, 50@60c.\nRutabagas Canadian, per 100 lbs.,\n$1.50 @1.75.\nShallots \u2014Louisiana, bbls., $7.00 @7.50.\nSpinach Texas, per bushel, 50 60c.\nSquash\u2014HubParo, doz.. $3.00@3.50.\nString Beans Florida, hampers, wax\nor green, $12.00@14.00.\nTomatoes California, prepacked, 6-\nbasket crates. $7.00@7.50; hot house, per\nlb.. 30 35c.\nSweet Potatoes Tennessee, hampers,\nNancy Halls. $2.00@2.25; New Jersey.\nJerseys, $2.25@2.50; Indiana, bushels,\n$2.75@3.00.\nTurnips Home-grown, bushels, tops\noff, 75@85c; new, Louisiana, bbls., $4.50\n@5.00.\nPRODUCE MARKETS.\nBeans Navies, choice, hand-picked,\nper 100 lbs. (sacks included), ?5.10@\n5.35; Red Kidney, $7.25@7.75; Brown\nSwedish, $6.00@6.50; Lima Beans. $7.50\n@B.OO.\nBees Wax Choice to fancy, per lb.,\nbright, 28@30c; dark. 23@25c, and\ndown to 20c.\nHoney Comb, per case, 25 l-]b. sec\ntions, fancy, white, $5,50@6.00; dark,\n$4.75@5.00; mixed sells at around $5.00\nExtracted, lb., white cloved. U@l2c;\namber. 9@loe.\nPeas\u2014Per 100 lbs. inew, 100-lb. sacks),\ngreen. $3.75@4.00; Scotch, $3.75@4.00;\nwhite, $3.75@4.00; marrow fats, $4.00@\n5.00; split peas, yellow. $5 75@6.00;\ngreen, $5.75@6.00.\nPop Corn \u2014Quotable per 100 lbs., ears.\n$3.00@3.50: shelled. do. $4 00@5.00:\nbroken, poor. less.\nTallow\u2014Prime. 9% @10c; No. 1, solid.\n6%@7c; No. 2. 5%@6c; cakes. 7%@Bc;\nrough. 2%@3c.\nWool\u2014Medium, per ib\u201e 30@32c: low.\n2S@3oc.\n^HOMLGAJW\nis Home\nWithout a\nQuality Radishes Fr\nf 3CARIET\nnil GLOBE Wtonch\nIg. ^Tb^AKFAST.\nk I\nTIPPED\nw\nLONG\nV- m WHITE\nX W\\ VIENNA.\nICICLE. V nX\nRADISH TYPES.\nThe radish is the one vegetable\nthat every gardener is bound to\nplant and, fortunately, it is one\nvegetable with which he is bound to\nsucced, for it is difficult to do any\nthing to a radish that will make a\nw\u2019hole crop fail. But quality rad\nishes are seldom grown for the very\nreason that they are so easy to\ngrow no pains are taken with them;\nand they are planted thick and left\nto-' struggle and get their thinning\nas those that have had the best\nchance and have made the biggest\nroots are pulled.\nThe maturity of the radish will\nbe hastened and the crispness and\nsnappy flavor be much improved if\nYour Income Tax\nThis is a series of articles based\non the revenue act of 1926 and\nthe latest regulations relating to\nthe income tax. The reduction\nrates, increase in exemptions,\ncredit on earned income applying\nto earned net income not to ex\nceed $20,000, and other changes\nin tax legislation, in comparison\nwith the revenue act of 1914 are\nset forth.\nNO. 24.\nInquiries received by the Bureau\nof Internal Revenue indicate confu\nsion In the minds of the writers con\ncerning the difference between bus\niness expenditures and business ex\npenses. Business expenditures are\nnot always business expenses with\nin the meaning of the income tax\nlaw. A merchant may build an ad\ndition to his store at a cost of $25,-\n000. This is a capital expenditure\nfor an addition to his assets.' Cap\nital expenditures are not deductible.\nDistinction is made between ex\npenditure for an asset and expendi\nture in connection with an asset. If\nthe merchant should, during the\nyear, spend .SSOO on repairs to his\nbuilding, such as repainting the roof\nor repairing broken windows, he\nmay deduct such amount as a bus\niness expense.\nMedical, law, or other profession\nal books, machinery, tools, imple\nments, or surgical instruments pur\nchased by a taxpayer for use in his\nbusiness, trade or profession, and\nwhich are of a permanent charac\nter, are capital assets, and their\ncost is not deductible.\nN.Y. Stock Market Closing Prices I\nClose.\nAllied Chemical and Dye 136%\nAllis-Chalmers 91 Yi\nAmerican Agri. Chem 13%\nAmerican Beet Sugar 24\nAmerican Can 46%\nAmerican Car and F0undry.,..104%\nAmerican and Foreign Power.. 20%\nAmerican Locomotive 111%\nAm. Smelt and Ref 142%\nAm. Sugar Ref 82%\nAm. T. and T 155%\nAm. Tobacco B 120%\nAm. Woolen 25%\nAm. Zinc 9%\nzxnaconda Copper 46%\nA. T. and S. F 166%\nA. T. and S. F., pfd 100%!\nBaldwin Locomotive 176%\nBaltimore and Ohio 111%\nBethlehem Steel 45%\nCalif. Packing 66%\nCalif. Petroleum 31%\nCanadian Pacific 176%\nCase Thresh. Machine 144\nCerro de Pasco 61%\nC. and 0 157%\nChicago, Great Western 14%\nC. M. and St. Paul 13%\nC. M. and St. Paul pfd 22%\nChicago and North Western.... 82\nC. R. 1 and P 76%\nChile Copper 35\nChrysler Motor 42%\nColorado Fuel Iron 58%\nConsolidated Gas 100\nCorn Products Refining Co 49%\nCrucible Steel 84\nDupont De Nemours Co 177\nElec. P. L. ctfs 17%\nErie R. R 43%\nFamous Players Lasky 108%\nGeneral Asphalt 83%\nGeneral Electric 83\nGeneral Motors 156%\nGoodrich B. F 54%\nGreat Northern, pfd 86%\nGreat Northern Ore., ctfs 22%\nGreene Cananea Mining 32%\nHudson Motor Corporation 63%\nIllinois Central 123%\nIndian Ref 9\nInspiration Copper 23%\nnn Spring to Winter\nthey are thinned to two inches\napart, or even one inch in the little\nbreakfast types, as soon as the seed\nis through the ground. This gives\nthem a chance to develop their roots\nas fast as they can.\nRadishes have been cultivated by\nmen for many ages. In medieval\ntimes barons spiceci the feasts in\nthe castles with dishes of the long\nand very hot varieties now grown\nfor summer use, such as Chartier\nand White Strassburg. These take\ntwice as long to mature as the\nearly varieties now available to us,\nsuch as the earliest White Olive,\nTwenty Day, Saxa and Scarlet\nGlobe. Improvements in most veg\netables run decidedly to the produc\ntion of varieties which mature ear\nlier, and probably the greatest\nadvantage which we have over our\nancestors in the vegetable garden is\nthe possession of more early kinds.\nThe early radishes are more ten\nder and milder in flavor than the\nlate sorts, but at the same time,\nquick to turn pithy, so they must\nbe eaten as soon as they mature.\nIn selecting radishes to grow, in\norder to provide these peppy roots\nfor his table throughout the season,\nthe gardener must decide whether\nto depend upon periodical sowings\nof an early variety (about every 10\ndays), or co sow, approximately at\nthe same time, an early, midseason\nand late variety, which will mature\none after the other. His decision\nshould be based upon his personal\npreference, remembering that those\nwhich mature later are likely to\nhave a stronger flavor.\nWinter radishes sown in the lat\nter part of June produce huge roots\nof very mild flavor which can be\nkept a long time in good condition,\nand a crop of them will add a wel\ncome dish to the winter menu.\nGARY DENIES\nHE WILL QUIT\nNEW YORK Reports that he\nintended to retire from the chair\nmanship of the United States Steel\ncorporation were denied by Elbert\nH. Gary today. He declared that\nhe had not considered resigning,\nbut intended to remain \u201cin harness\u201d\nfor some time, and that so far as he\nwas aware, his associates had not\neven considered the possibilty.\nHe said that rumors of this or\nlike nature might harm business,\nand that in no case should they be\ngiven publicity unless verified.\nAt the same time that Mr. Gary\u2019s\nstatement was issued, an article ap\npeared here forecasting appoint\nment of Nathan L. Miller \u201cin the\nevent of Mr. Gary\u2019s retirement.\u201d\nMr. Miller, it is said, is favored by\nGary to succeed him, because of\nbis judicial experience.\nThe purchase price of an auto\nmobile, even when used wholly for\nbusiness or professional purposes is\na capital expenditure and not de\nductible. The cost of gasoline, re\npairs, and upkeep of an automobile\nis deductible if used wholly in bus\niness. If used partly for business\nand partly for pleasure and con\nvience of the taxpayer and his fam\nilly, such cost should be apportioned\naccordingly. The proportions of\ncost justly attributable to business\npurposes is deductible as a neces\nsary expense.\nFriday\nClose.\nInternational Harvester 156\nKansas City Southern 47%\nKennecott Copper 61\nKresge (S S) 49\nLehigh Valley 120%\nLouisville and Nashville 132%\nMarland Oil 57%\nMiami Copper 15\nMissouri, Kansas and Texas.... 37\nMissouri Pacific 44%\nMontgomery Ward 62\nNational Biscuit A.\u2014 98\nNational Lead 171%\nNevada Consolidated Copper.... 14%\nNew York Central 145\nN. Y\u201e N. H. and H 56\nNorthern Pacific 85\nPacific Gas and Electric 31%\nPacific Oil 7%\nPennsylvania Railroad 57%\nPeoples Gas (Chicago) 129%\nPure Oil 28%\nRay Consolidated Copper 15%\nReading 108%\nReplogle Steel 11%\nRepublic Iron and Steel..., 62%\nRoyal Dutch 53%\nSears-Roebuck 52%\nSinclair Cons. Oil 21%\nSo. Pacific 108%\nSouth. Ry 122%\nStandard Oil, Calif 59%\nStandard Oil, N. J 39%\nStudebaker 53\nTenn. Copper 12%\nTexas and Pacific 60\u20194\nTimken Bearing 92\":.\nTobacco Products 188%\nTranscontinental Oil _4%\nUnion Oil Calif 53%\nUnion Pacific 165\nIT. S. Rubber Co 63%\nIT. S. Steel Corp 157%\nU. S. Steel, pfd 130\nVanadium Corp 39%\nVa. Carolina Chem 10%\nWabash 57%\nWabash, pfd. A 81%\nWestinghouse Elec. Mach. 70\nWillys Overland 21%\nYellow Truck Coach* 26%\nFriday\nPAGE TEN\nPennsy Plans to\nElectrify Gotham\nDivision, Report\nPHILADELPHIA Tentative\nplans for the construction near\nTrenton, on the Delaware river, of a\ngreat power plant by the Pennsyl\nvania road, the Philadelphia Rapid\nTransit Co. and The United Gas\nImprovement Co. forecast electrifi\ncation of the Philadelphia-New\nYork division of the Pennsylvania\nwithin a comparatively short time.\n\u201cIn anticipation of the extensive\nelectrification plans which the\nPennsylvania railroad has under\ncontemplation,\u201d said a statement is\nsued by the company, \u201cand the ne\ncessity for large amounts of a 25-\ncycle electrical energy, the engi\nneers of the Pennsylvania road\nhave for some time been given con\nsideration to the erection of a power\nplant sufficient for its needs.\u201d\nRAIL TRAFFIC\nDROPS HERE\nFreight traffic in Milwaukee in\nJanuary showed a drop both in\ncomparison with the corresponding\nmonth last year and the preceding\nmonth, despite an increase in re\nceipts over the same month in 1926,\naccording to figures issued yester\nday by three railroads.\nTotal traffic, comprising receipts\nand shipments combined, during the\nmonth here came to 1,906,926,360\npounds, against 1,914,062,749\npounds in January, 1926, and 1,981,-\n270,886 in December.\nReceipts totaled 1,136,672,3^4\npounds compared with 1,113,096,355\na year ago and 1,155,949,235 a\nmonth ago.\nShipments aggregated 770,254,016\npounds, while a year ago they came\nto 800.966,394 pounds and a month\nago, 825,321,651.\nHasten Waterway,\nLumbermen Ask\nCHICAGO Resolutions urging\nthat legislation be passed to hasten\nthe construction of the Mississippi\nand St. Lawrence waterways were\nadopted yesterday by the Illinois\nLumber and Material Dealers\u2019 Assn,\nat its convention in Chicago yes\nterday.\nFreight rates that upbuild one\ncommunity at the expense of anoth\ner were condemned by the dealers.\nThey recommended the conserva\ntion of forests and the passage of\nsound, economic laws to aid agri\nculture.\nJ. W. Mackemer of Peoria was\nelected president of the association.\nCash Grain\nBarley\nSlow and unchanged. Receipts light.\nDemand fair from maltsters and ship\npers. Choice to fancy. 48 to 50 lb. test,\nquotable at 82@83c; fair to good, 44 to\n47 lb. test, 77 082 c; lightweight, 40 to\n43 lb. test, 70@78c; feed, 65@72c.\nCorn\nStrong and l@2c higher with better\nbasis. Receipts small. Demand good,\nlocal and shipping. No. 4 yellow quot\nable 9@llc under May. No. 4 white at\n10 012 c under May. No. 4 mixed, 10\n12c under May, as to moisture and color.\nOats\nSteady and unchanged with futures.\nReceipts light. Good demand for bright;\npoor slow. No. 3 white quotable May to\n3c under.\nRye\nFirm and wanted with better basis.\nReceipts light. Good demand from ship\npers. No. 2 quotable at $1.04 1.04%,\nranging at 2%@3c under May price.\nHeavy discounts prevail for wet parcels\nand out of condition.\nWheat\nSteady and unchanged with futures.\nReceipts small. Good demand for choice\ngrades. No. 1 hard winter, l@3c over\nMay, l@2c more for dark. No. 2 hard\nMay to 4c under. No. 3 hard, s@loc\nunder May. No. 1 red winter, 1@ 2c un\nder May; No. 2 red, 3@4c under May\nprice; No. 3 red, s@lo